Sr. the 24: curitt remitt you £80: flemish on Pieter De ka of Bruges
payable in Lille by michiel vander cruysse, which was due yeasterday I hope
you neglected not to demand payement, which in case you did I have fore
yd acctt: I can not butt wonder to have non from you the more because
I f inde you drew £100: flemish on mee att aso the 21: curitt & give
mee no advise, I must blame you very much for so doing, besides that
you draw without order, & where I promised to send you remises which
is all att present o

London.. John Loyd -
th
Sr. my last to you was on the 18. crritt to which please to be referred
sence recd. yd of 13 ditto I hope Ben. klarck before now arrived & do
wish the druggetts may prove to content: returne you thancks
for accepting my bill, what is due to you by that shall be made
good to content, in case you do not make use of itt here
the tykes rise everij mart day & non or few to be had, I have
engageed about 100 peeces, butt I heare not one word of the
maker, though I writte them everij week, so that I intend
for turnhout mij self to make them comply to their under
takeings, thread is risen about 20 p.cet. a governo
flax here is almost ruined up on the field so that the old is
risen near 30 Pcento which the dree season hath caused
now as to mr. Luke norton, he is still a life in our cast &
doth go by the name of m. moore, and is the vere same of which you
gave mee the description, he is not in the least detained for Religion
and though he ware turck or iew, or a headen, yett non here was ever
punished for religion itt zeems: when he was att the hague, as
also att Brussels he hath sedetiously spoken of some ministers of
the king of spaine, which for recompence, have clapt him in
prison, butt as yett non accused him, itt is beleaved that sir Richard
Bulstroide yd kings resident att Brussels will help him out for
the honour of the nation, though mr. norton is not much his freind
some say that he hath proposed great things concerning governement
and as if he should have had some correspondency in france to preiudice
of these countreys, butt that he denijes, att least he hath bragged
extreamly up on forces & monyes what will become of him non knows
if I can do you or any of yd freinds any service freely command him that
London Luy knightley
@ 28 ditto

Sr. I have before mee yd of 13: curitt bij which perceave that yd ague doth still hinder
you from bussynes for which am sorrij yett wee must have patientie with what
comes from almighty god I am much obliged that not withstanding, you will
take the paines te provide 5 duble reds & ship them off pr. first for which returne
you thankes, & could wish you were pleased to duble the quantitie, & to make itt
10 duble peeces as desired the 4:curitt in which doing you will highly oblige mee
& I'll assure you I shall take itt as a perticular fovour, whilst I remaine
london will scawen
@ 28 ditto
th
Sr. my last to you was on the 18: curitt sence recd yd of 10 ditto as for our
callicos I have no vent, butt hope itt will come in after harvest for now is itt
the deadest time of all the yeare I have sent you a pack of tijkes which is
detained att Gant because a ship was sunck betwixt gant & Bruges & there
bj lost the opportunitie of coning with Ben klarck, butt now John
collinier will bring itt over which god sending safe hope will prove to
content. thread is rissen above 20 Pcento so tykes must follow accordinly
where fore do not sell y without proffitt to yd satisfaction for Jcan not send you
one peece more for the mentioned prijses. as for the guild leather hanghings I have been
as much disapointed as ever I was: as I have told you they were a makeing
according to what the maker hath promised, & continued, so to delay mee from
time to time & shewd mee now & then some peeces & now he hath delivered
them to some body elce, & sayes that them I sace were bespoaken long before, &
that mine should be the same, which he opentley says he did to keep mee
bj the hand, till he should be att leasure to serve mee which now he is, butt
nevertheless demands yett 3 months time so that I did not aggree because
I know not if itt should be to yd content: itt should be needles to have one
word aboutt itt, in case wee had more then one maker in figures upon
guild Leather, where fore I could as yett not serve you there in as I exspecte
nevert less if yd freind will stay out the time I shall compleat the parcell
butt mee thinkes, he should do better to in order his guild leather to be of
an other pattarne, as most are in use, of a peirle culloured ground &
fruits painted out to the life of which I have a new pattarne such as
I have sent of late for England bij order of m. John Loijd, and for
Irland which I should exspect would give content: for the figures
will cost as much againe, whoever what you shall order shall
be performed, whilst I remaine
